  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the evolution of anti-money laundering (AML) legislation:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US) first required financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Limited initial focus on detecting criminal financial activities\n\n2. International Coordination\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Created global standards and recommendations for combating money laundering\n- Developed comprehensive policy frameworks\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- 1990s: Expanded international cooperation\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Introduced customer due diligence protocols\n- Criminalized money laundering as a specific offense\n\n4. Post-9/11 Developments\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Increased financial surveillance\n- Strengthened counter-terrorism financing measures\n- Expanded reporting obligations\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Enhanced digital transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency regulation\n- Broader beneficial ownership transparency\n- Complex international information-sharing mechanisms\n\n6. Current Focus\n- Risk-based approach\n- Advanced technological detection systems\n- Continuous regulatory adaptation\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\nThe legislation has progressively become more comprehensive, technologically sophisticated, and globally coordinated.",
